Stinging Nettle
Urtica Dioica and other species.
Family;
Urticaceae

Parts Used;
Aerial parts

Energy and
Flavour;
Bland, slightly bitter, cool.

Constituents;
chlorophyll, indoles including histamine and serotonic,
formic acid, acetylcholine,  vitamin C, A , silicon,
potassium, iron,  protein and fibre.

Properties;
Astringent, diuretic, tonic, hemostatic, galactagogue,
expectorant, nutritive.

Perennial

Alien

Nettles can be found growing in waste places and are very
abundant. They grow to a height of 15 to 24 inches with
stiff hairs on the stalks and the leaves are toothed and heart
shaped and about 2 to 4 inches long. The flowers are in
clusters at the leaf axils and are a greenish colour. They
are unisexual with either male or female on a given plant,
or on the same plant with males in upper leaf axils and
females flowers on the lower leaf axils. They are about
1/12" long.  The flowers appear from June to September.
They should be harvested when the flowers are in bloom for
medicinal use.

Caution must be used when harvesting these plants as the
small stiff hairs can cause a severe burning skin irritation.
When they are young they can be cooked and served as
greens or used in soups and stews. The family and genus
names come from the Latin URO, which means "I burn".
If you do get a rash from harvesting them try rubbing the
freshly bruised leaves of yellow dock or plantain over the
affected area. They often grow nearby the Nettles.

Traditionally in Europe, the leaf tea is used as a blood
purifier or blood builder, what we now call an alternative.
Nettles are also used as diuretics, astringents, for anemia,
gout, glandular diseases, asthma, urinary stones, nephritis
and cystitis,  rheumatism, poor circulation, enlarged spleen,
mucous discharges of the lungs, internal bleeding, diarrhea
and dysentery.

For bleeding such as endometriosis, or uterine bleeding,
combine equal parts of nettle leaf with agrimony, bayberry
and cinnamon barks. Steep in boiling water for twenty
minutes and take a cupful every hour, tapering off as bleeding
subsides.

A clinical study of nettle roots has found them to be highly
effective for the treatment of enlarged prostate. The roots
contain high amounts of sterols, especially sitosterol and
isolectins, which stimulate the production of white blood
cells that counteract infections and inflammations.

Studies suggest that Nettles are a good Central Nervous
System depressant, are anti-bacterial, and inhibit the
effects of adrenaline. The Germans have been using the
root in treatments for prostate cancer and the Russians are
using the leaves in alcohol for cholecystitis (inflammation of
the gall bladder), and hepatitis.

For the treatment of eczema Nettles will combine well with
Figwort and Burdock.

Preparation and Dosage;

Infusion;   pour a cup of boiling water onto 1 - 3 teaspoonfuls
of the dried herb and leave to infuse for 10 to 15 minutes. This
can be drunk three times a day.

Tincture;   1 to 4 millilitres three times a day.

References;

Dominion Herbal College Text
David Hoffmann, The New Holistic Herbal. 1990
Michael Tierra, The Way of Herbs. 1998
Peterson Field Guides,
Eastern and Central Medicinal Plants.

