 Section 6         AROMA ARMY TO THE RESCUE

                         by Jan Blacktopp, R.M.T.
                         Registered Massage Therapist
                         Certified Aromatherapist
                         blacktopp@interhop.net

                 Read about Jan Blacktopp on our Meet the Team
                 page; http://www.Life-Choices.com/team.html

 ----------

    Most of us have a strong need to protect what is "near
and dear" - especially those places which provide us with
sanctuary and nourishment.  In today's busy and often
stressful world, we seek quiet places where nature abounds
in order to feel connected again to Mother Earth.  No wonder
that the garden has become the focal point for urban dwellers
to find respite from concrete, noise and dust.  Country gardens
also provide both a charming and practical environment where
birds and butterflies add their colour to those of wildflowers
and food crops. Even the "container garden" on the apartment
balcony can provide that so important connection to nature in
the inner city.

    Whenever we consider aromas in the garden we immediately
think of the beautiful perfumes emitted from our favourite flowers
and plants.  However, aromas have another valuable and lesser-
known role to play - they can actually protect the garden from
destruction and disease.  In the plant world, aroma is a matter
of life and death.  Some reproduction depends on the transfer
of pollen by bees, butterflies and moths.  The most highly-scented
flowers tend to be fertilized by butterflies & moths.  Fruity aromas
attract beetles which aid in fertilization and even unpleasant fishy
odours bring the needed dung and flesh flies to do the job.

    Aromas also protect certain plants from predators by making
them smell repugnant or rendering them poisonous to insects.

    Willow and alder trees when under attack by tent caterpillars
will produce strong terpenes and tannins in their leaves making
them undigestable to the enemy.  Not only do the trees fight back
but it is thought that they communicate by aroma to others of their
species who are at risk.  The threatened trees receive the aromatic
message and make the bio-chemical changes in their leaves before
the caterpillars arrive.  How sophisticated nature is!

    Now for some practical garden tips.  Roses intercropped with
garlic and onions not only are protected from predators and fungi
but their fragrances are enhanced as well.  Carrots planted beside
marigolds benefit from the protective aroma of the flowers.

    Essential oils act as natural pest deterrents and slow the growth
of bacteria, viruses, fungi and mould on plants.  A good way to
protect the garden is to plant protective varieties among vulnerable
ones.  Another method is to add the essential oils to the watering can
or use as a spray.  Basil can be planted alongside tomatoes or basil
oil in water can be used to protect the plants.  Tomatoes, treated
with basil oil even have an enhanced flavour.

    Roses love garlic, basil and thyme.  Thyme and lavender protect
all vegetable plants.  Four to eight drops of essential oil in four litres
of water make an excellent spray for flowers, fruits and veggies.
You can even place strings between the garden rows and spray the
strings with the essential oil/water mixture.

    Ants are deterred by peppermint oil and you can clear a nest
quickly by placing two neat drops of this oil directly on the nest.
Mice hate peppermint as well.

    To deter slugs, snails, mice, cats, dogs and ground-moving insects
from attacking your plants, bury a plastic tub with the top level to the
ground.  Add four drops of essential oil such as peppermint, spearmint,
thyme or eucalyptus.  Renew when needed.  Cats however love
citronella and dogs are attracted to lavender.

    If you want a very detailed list of essential oils to deter specific pest,
consult your aromatherapy book.

    Well there you are-an aromatic army is available to protect your
garden sanctuary.  No need to use those pesticides and chemicals.
Let nature by your ally.

Happy Gardening!

Reference:
Fragrant Pharmacy by Valerie Worwood

